        <Text textformat="02"><![CDATA[<p>Under every city lies a second city. Water mains and sewer tunnels, cable ducts and data exchanges, the ancient buried rivers and the brand-new fibre — all of it invisible to the people walking above it, yet all of it indispensable to modern life.</p><p>In <em>Invisible Infrastructure</em>, Kwame Osei-Bonsu takes us beneath six world cities — London, Lagos, Tokyo, New York, Mumbai and Rotterdam — to reveal the extraordinary systems that keep them alive. Richly illustrated and compellingly argued, this is a book about engineering, politics, inequality, and what cities owe their citizens.</p>]]></Text>
      </TextContent>
      <TextContent>
        <TextType>23</TextType>
        <ContentAudience>00</ContentAudience>
        <Text textformat="06">Chapter One: What Lies Beneath London

The Thames Tideway Tunnel is nine years late and three billion pounds over budget. On the morning I descend into the excavation at Chambers Wharf, the project manager tells me this is normal. "Every major infrastructure project in history has been late and over budget," she says. "The ones that ran on time and on budget are the ones that weren't ambitious enough." I write this in my notebook and wonder if she is right.</Text>
